can be distinguished from all congeners by their strongly upturned cerci tips ending on a long acute spine (
<figureCitation box="[599,680,1497,1522]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,723,1896]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,711,1901]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Male S 10, lateral view. (a) and (b) by RWG." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227949/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Fig. 
<number box="[652,680,1497,1522]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
b; not strongly upturned or not ending in a long acute spine in other species, 
<figureCitation box="[249,345,1533,1558]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,723,1896]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,711,1901]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Male S 10, lateral view. (a) and (b) by RWG." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227949/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Figs. 
<number box="[317,345,1534,1558]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
a, c–i). They share the tubercle on venter of thorax with 
<taxonomicName box="[1027,1177,1534,1557]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequisetis">
<emphasis box="[1027,1177,1534,1557]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. aequisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1195,1339,1533,1558]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">
<emphasis box="[1195,1339,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. flavifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[292,371,1569,1594]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1999,2021]" captionTargetBox="[165,1389,1346,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,1335,1978]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Male thoracic venter, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227942/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Figs. 
<number box="[357,371,1569,1594]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
a–c; 
<number box="[428,444,1570,1593]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="7.0">7</number>
; venter of thorax smoothly convex or with a spine as long as twice its width in other species, 
<figureCitation box="[246,323,1605,1630]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1999,2021]" captionTargetBox="[165,1389,1346,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,1335,1978]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Male thoracic venter, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227942/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Figs. 
<number box="[308,323,1605,1630]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
d; 
<number box="[351,366,1606,1630]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="8.0">8</number>
), and the spurs of inner row of male hind tibiae of about uniform placement and length with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequisetis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. aequisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[277,433,1641,1666]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis box="[277,433,1641,1666]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[496,607,1641,1666]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phryne">
<emphasis box="[496,607,1641,1666]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. phryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[623,700,1641,1666]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1994]" captionTargetBox="[159,1415,1105,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,1093,1951]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male hind tibiae, lateral view of inner surface." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227938/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Figs. 
<number box="[686,700,1641,1666]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
a–b, e, g; closely set and peg-like at medial 
<quantity box="[1195,1274,1641,1666]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.382" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" unit="in" value="0.33">0.33 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[1281,1436,1641,1666]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonardina">
<emphasis box="[1281,1436,1641,1666]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. leonardina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or shorter and more closely set at basal 
<quantity box="[612,755,1677,1702]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5875" metricValueMax="1.905" metricValueMin="1.27" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" unit="in" value="0.625" valueMax="0.75" valueMin="0.5">0.50–0.75 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[764,905,1677,1702]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">
<emphasis box="[764,905,1677,1702]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. flavifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[921,1000,1677,1702]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1972,1994]" captionTargetBox="[159,1415,1105,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,1093,1951]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male hind tibiae, lateral view of inner surface." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227938/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Figs. 
<number box="[986,1000,1677,1702]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
c–d, f). Male vesica spermalis is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[355,502,1714,1737]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequisetis">
<emphasis box="[355,502,1714,1737]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. aequisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but its medio-ectal distal process is distinctly shorter than the latero-ectal distal lobes (
<figureCitation box="[226,306,1749,1774]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1683,1705]" captionTargetBox="[165,1432,242,1562]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,231,1580]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 11. Male vesica spermalis, lateral (above) and ventral (below) view. l. e.: latero-ectal sclerotized distal process; m. e.: medio-ectal sclerotized distal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227947/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Fig. 
<number box="[279,306,1749,1774]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
b; medio-ectal distal process only slightly shorter than latero-ectal lobes in 
<taxonomicName box="[1156,1301,1750,1773]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequisetis">
<emphasis box="[1156,1301,1750,1773]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. aequisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and longer than latero-ectal lobes or vestigial to absent in other species, 
<figureCitation box="[899,995,1785,1810]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1683,1705]" captionTargetBox="[165,1432,242,1562]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,231,1580]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 11. Male vesica spermalis, lateral (above) and ventral (below) view. l. e.: latero-ectal sclerotized distal process; m. e.: medio-ectal sclerotized distal process." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227947/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Figs. 
<number box="[968,995,1786,1810]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
a, c–f). Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1237,1343,1785,1810]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berlai">
<emphasis box="[1237,1343,1785,1810]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. berlai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName box="[485,645,1821,1846]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonardina">
<emphasis box="[485,645,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. leonardina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the radial planate consisting of three cells and the base of Fw discoidal planate with one cell (
<figureCitation box="[507,573,1857,1882]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1857,1879]" captionTargetBox="[166,1428,208,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1836]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male wings. d. f.: base of discoidal field; r. p.: radial planate; sub.: cells between subtriangle and hind margin of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227939/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Fig. 
<number box="[559,573,1857,1882]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
b; four or five and two respectively in 
<taxonomicName box="[1003,1158,1857,1882]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonardina">
<emphasis box="[1003,1158,1857,1882]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. leonardina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1172,1237,1857,1882]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1857,1879]" captionTargetBox="[166,1428,208,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1836]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male wings. d. f.: base of discoidal field; r. p.: radial planate; sub.: cells between subtriangle and hind margin of wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227939/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
Fig. 
<number box="[1223,1237,1857,1882]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
f). The number of cells between Fw subtriangle and hind margin of wing is variable in 
<taxonomicName box="[935,1036,1893,1918]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berlai">
<emphasis box="[935,1036,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. berlai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and females are undistinguishable morphologically from those of 
<taxonomicName box="[501,645,1930,1953]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequisetis">
<emphasis box="[501,645,1930,1953]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. aequisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[659,798,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">
<emphasis box="[659,798,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. flavifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[860,970,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phryne">
<emphasis box="[860,970,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. phryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1111,1267,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis box="[1111,1267,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">N. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
unknown).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="125" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1173,2026]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="125" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1965,1990]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[323,533,1965,1990]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berlai">
<emphasis box="[323,533,1965,1990]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="124">Nephepeltia berlai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described as having one cell under the Fw subtriangle. Even though this is the most commonly observed condition (
<number box="[626,655,2001,2026]" pageId="3" pageNumber="124" value="65.0">65</number>
% of examined specimens), this character was found to be variable among specimens within the same population: of the five males from Arroyo Ovie in 
<collectingCountry box="[1120,1225,152,176]" name="Paraguay" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, two have one cell in both wings, one has two cells in both wings, and two have two cells in one wing and one in the other; of the six males from Anyico in 
<collectingCountry box="[401,515,223,248]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, four have one cell in both wings, one has two cells in both wings, and one has one wing with one cell and one with two; of the three males from Fazenda Santana in 
<collectingCountry box="[1065,1136,260,285]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, two have both wings with one cell, and one has one wing with two cells.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="125" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,332,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[360,569,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Nephepeltia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berlai">
<emphasis box="[360,569,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Nephepeltia berlai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the most restricted distribution of the genus, being known only from SE 
<collectingCountry box="[151,222,367,392]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[235,340,368,392]" name="Paraguay" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, and NE 
<collectingCountry box="[449,560,367,392]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[577,662,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1349,1370]" captionTargetBox="[164,1422,205,1299]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 16. Distribution of Nephepeltia species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227952/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Fig. 
<number box="[631,662,367,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Its last stadium larva was described based on specimens collected along marginal vegetation at an artificial pond rich in decomposing organic matter (
<bibRefCitation author="Dalzochio" box="[1088,1280,404,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" refString="Dalzochio, M. S. (2009) Descricao da larva de ultimo estadio de Nephepeltia berlai Santos, 1950 (Odonata: Libellulidae). EntomoBrasilis, 2 (3), 702 - 72." type="journal article" year="2009">
Dalzochio, 
<number box="[1219,1280,404,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
